          "body": "Romans 5:14 provides the New Testament's own commentary on Genesis 5: 'death reigned from Adam until Moses, even over those who had not sinned in the likeness of the offense of Adam.' Paul is not theorizing; he is reading Genesis 5. The chapter is his textual basis for the claim that death's dominion is universal and chronologically total — from the first man to the lawgiver. But the chapter also shows that grace persisted within death's reign. The line of Seth continued. Enoch was translated. Noah was born. The covenant God who pronounced the curse also kept a remnant alive through every generation of the antediluvian world. This is the chapter's pastoral payoff: death is real, universal, and relentless — and God works through it, around it, and ahead of it. His purposes are not finally derailed by the very judgment He pronounced."
