        "number": 4,
        "title": "Noah — the hope at the end of the line",
        "range": "5:28-32",
        "excerpt": "He called his name Noah, saying, 'This one will give us rest from our work and from the toil of our hands arising from the ground which the LORD has cursed.'",
        "body": "The chapter's closing movement introduces Noah — the tenth patriarch, the only one besides Enoch who receives more than the bare formula — through the theological speech of his father Lamech. The speech in 5:29 is the chapter's only direct discourse and its only prophetic utterance, and it carries enormous freight.\n\nLamech names his son with a theological declaration. The name Noah (noach — rest) is explained by the verb nacham (to comfort, to give rest). This is not a perfect etymological match in Hebrew — the roots are distinct — but Moses is using a deliberate sound-play to bind the name to the prophetic expectation. 'This one will give us rest (*nacham*).' The word nacham encompasses comfort, consolation, and relief from suffering — it is the word Isaiah uses of God's eschatological comfort of His people (Isaiah 40:1; 49:13; 51:12). Lamech is not merely expressing parental hope; he is voicing a theological conviction shaped by the accumulated suffering of the genealogy.\n\nThe specific object of the hoped-for rest is 'our work and from the toil of our hands arising from the ground which the LORD has cursed.' Lamech explicitly names the Adamic curse of Genesis 3:17-19. He looks back across nine generations of toil and death and believes that in Noah he is seeing something new — a relief from the curse that has defined antediluvian human existence. He is not wrong, but he is not fully right either. Noah will bring relief (the Flood cleanses the earth; Genesis 8-9 establishes a covenant; Genesis 9:20 has Noah farming — tilling the same ground under now-modified conditions). But the curse is not lifted by Noah; it is merely suspended. The ultimate nacham awaits the one Noah typologically points toward: the seed of the woman of Genesis 3:15, the one who will crush the serpent's head and bring the full reversal of the curse (Romans 8:20-21; Revelation 22:3).\n\nIn the canonical arc of Scripture, Noah's position as the 'second Adam' is established by the verbal echoes: God blesses Noah as He blessed Adam (Genesis 9:1 / 1:28), gives him dominion over animals (9:2 / 1:28), and establishes a covenant with all creation through him (9:8-17). The genealogy of Genesis 5 is the bridge that leads from the first Adam to the second. And the second Adam is himself a bridge to the Last Adam (1 Corinthians 15:45) — the one in whom the hope of nacham will finally and fully be realized.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Noach* (Noah) — related to the root *nuach* (to rest, to settle). *Nacham* (comfort, give rest) — the verb of the naming speech — is phonetically close but etymologically distinct; Moses is using assonance for theological effect, not etymology. *Yehovah* (LORD) appears only in 5:29 in the entire chapter — the covenant name surfaces only at the moment of covenant hope. *Adamah* (ground / soil) — the word for the cursed earth, distinct from *adam* (humankind); the ground cursed in 3:17 is the same *adamah* from which *adam* was made (2:7)."
